/*
:name: untyped_mux_cond
:type: equiv
:verilog_top: untyped_mux_cond.top
:pyrope_top: top
*/

// An UNTYPED `mut`/`const` bound to a runtime value, then used as a mux
// condition through `==`/`!=`.  Such a variable bakes no scalar data leaf (its
// declare's type slot is `prim_type_none`), so its bundle is zero-entry —
// exactly the shape of the empty tuple `()`.  upass.constprop used to tell the
// two apart by `get_mode() != unknown`, which answers "was this name declared?"
// and not "is this a tuple" — so every untyped declared var folded as `()`, and
// `() == <scalar>` is unconditionally false.  The mux condition became a
// compile-time constant and one arm was silently dropped: WRONG hardware, no
// diagnostic.  The guard is now positive tuple evidence (value_kind == tuple).
//
// Each output below folded to the `x` arm before the fix (`ack`/`req` dropped
// entirely).  A no-type-annotation variable is the whole point — do NOT "fix"
// this test by adding `:u1`, which is itself one of the maskers.
pub comb top(ack:u1, req:u1, x:u4, y:u4) -> (sel:u4, sel2:u4, sel3:u4) {
  // the minimal case: an untyped COPY of a runtime input (no operator at all)
  mut cond = ack
  sel = if cond != 0 { x } else { y }

  // two DISTINCT untyped runtime vars compared to each other: folded `() == ()`
  // => true, so two unrelated signals compared equal at compile time
  mut c1 = ack
  mut c2 = req
  sel2 = if c1 == c2 { x } else { y }

  // untyped var bound to a binary op, and a `const` binding rather than `mut`
  const c3 = ack | req
  sel3 = if c3 != 0 { x } else { y }
}
